<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="50172788-d951-5479-ade0-fc256e01da84" activityNameId="9aa82336-98da-433a-846b-3e2bac54c49a" parentActivityId="20e605d7-74eb-4ce6-aea7-6a33e3114f6a" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">2-methyl-2-butanol production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">tert-amyl alcohol</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> tert-pentanol</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with 2-methyl-2-butanol being ready for further transformation or transportation at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.
</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This data represents the production of 1 kg of pure 2-methyl-2-butanol via the hydration of 2-methyl-2-butene.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">2-methyl-2-butanol (CAS-No. 75-85-4, C5H11OH, Synonym: tert-amyl alcohol, tert-pentanol) is a colourless</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">liquid of characteristic odor. It is only sparingly miscible with water at 20 °C. However, it is</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">almost completely miscible with most organic solvents.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">2-methyl-2-butanol is employed as solvent for coating materials based on epoxy resins and polyurethanes,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">in the production of aryl pyruvic acids, and in the oxidation of olefins to the corresponding</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">carbonyl compounds. It is also used as a stabilizing agent for 1,1,1-trichloroethane, chlorinated C3 –</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">C4-hydrocarbons, and N,N,- dialkylallyl amines. The reaction of 2,2,6,6-tetramethyl-4-cyano-4-</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">hydroxypiperidine with 2-methyl-2-butanol yields highly active light stabilizers for polymers.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated  based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. At the same time, the energy consumption is based on data from literature sources.  Finally, the auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources.   For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">Frischknecht R., Jungbluth N., Althaus H.-J., Doka G., Dones R., Heck T.,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="13">Hellweg S., Hischier R., Nemecek T., Rebitzer G. and Spielmann M. (2007)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="14">Overview and Methodology. Final report ecoinvent v2.0 No. 1. Swiss Centre for</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="15">Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH, retrieved from: www.ecoinvent.org.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="16">Lappe, P., Hoffmann, T.: Pentanols. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="17">Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="18">G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="19">Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="20">http://www.mrw.interscience.wiley.com/ueic/articles</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled at the Global level. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields.  Furthermore, the source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Kim, Seungdo, and Michael Overcash "Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate‐to‐gate information for life cycle assessment." Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology: International Research in Process, Environmental &amp; Clean Technology 78.9 (2003): 995-1005. </text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset covers the production of 2-methyl-2-butanol by the hydration of 2-methyl-2-butene (isopentene).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Only a few industrial processes are known for the production of pentanols, namely, hydroformylation of butenes, hydrolysis of chloropentanes, and hydration of pentenes. Production of C5-alcohols from fusel oils by fermentation has been replaced mainly by the oxo synthesis and currently has little industrial importance. Production of pentanols from pentane by the Sharples process (chlorination of pentanes and subsequent hydrolysis) has also been largely replaced by oxo synthesis.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Hydration of pentenes</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">2-methyl-2-butanol is produced mainly by hydration of 2-methyl-2-butene (isopentene). There are</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">several processes which use different catalysts, e. g. acid ion exchangers, zeolites, layer silicates, formic</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">acid, HCl, SbCl3, ZnCl2, or acetic acid.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Reaction:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">C5H10 + H2O --&gt; C5H12O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">As there was no data available for the production of 2-methyl-2-butanol, the values for the consumption of the raw materials are calculated with an assumed yield of 95 % (Frischknecht et al. 2007). At the same time, the values for the energy use have been estimated with data from Chauvel 1989, who gives data for the production of isopropanol from the hydration of isopropylene. Hence, this process is considered to be similar to the hydration of 2-methyl-2-butene.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Reference:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Lappe, P., Hoffmann, T.: Pentanols. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossman G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: http://www.mrw.interscience.wiley.com/ueic/articles</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">Chauvel, A., Lefebvre, G.: Petrochemical processes. Vol 2: Major oxygenated,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">chlorinated, and nitrated derivatives. Institut français du pétrole publications.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="13">Éditions Technip, Paris 1989</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="14">Frischknecht R., Jungbluth N., Althaus H.-J., Doka G., Dones R., Heck T.,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="15">Hellweg S., Hischier R., Nemecek T., Rebitzer G. and Spielmann M. (2007)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="16">Overview and Methodology. Final report ecoinvent v2.0 No. 1. Swiss Centre for</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="17">Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH, retrieved from: www.ecoinvent.org.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="1989-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2022, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data (from 1989) for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015 to 2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989)</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
