      <elementaryExchange id="2217a201-5496-500d-aab4-df7f72406474" unitId="de5b3c87-0e35-4fb0-9765-4f3ba34c99e5" variableName="CW_u" casNumber="007732-18-5" amount="0.16946681229" isCalculatedAmount="true" mathematicalRelation="0.891930591 * ( 190 / 1000 )" sourceId="25bfa7f4-c8c3-47cc-813b-9f0da8e2a2db" sourceYear="1989" sourceFirstAuthor="Chauvel, A." elementaryExchangeId="fc1c42ce-a759-49fa-b987-f1ec5e503db1" formula="H2O">
        <name xml:lang="en">Water, cooling, unspecified natural origin</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">m3</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">This value is estimated based on the cooling requirements of a similar process. Specifically, this value represents the direct hydration of isopropanol, which was reported by Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989). The value of cooling water input for the latter process is 0.19 m3 per kg. All in all, we assume that the cooling requirements for the hydration of isopropylene, based on a Deutsche Texaco process, and 2-methyl-2-butene are similar.

At the same time, the latter amount was split between the following sources (1) "Water, cooling, unspecified natural origin", (2) "Water, river", and (3) "Water, well. in ground"</comment>
